315
00:15:19,537 --> 00:15:21,496
despite what Maybrook
did to me.

316
00:15:21,659 --> 00:15:22,835
And did that work?

317
00:15:23,012 --> 00:15:26,093
Well, I thought
pretty well at first.

318
00:15:26,216 --> 00:15:27,375
And then my wife wanted kids,

319
00:15:27,462 --> 00:15:28,968
and I couldn't tell her
why I didn't.

320
00:15:29,056 --> 00:15:31,014
I couldn't tell her
that I was afraid

321
00:15:31,295 --> 00:15:32,586
that I wouldn't be able
to protect them,

322
00:15:32,673 --> 00:15:34,905
the way that I couldn't
protect my brother.

323
00:15:34,993 --> 00:15:36,865
Objection.
Relevance?

324
00:15:36,998 --> 00:15:38,444
Overruled.

325
00:15:39,343 --> 00:15:40,769
You may continue.

326
00:15:41,193 --> 00:15:42,804
I don't know
what else to say.

327
00:15:44,522 --> 00:15:46,476
I thought I was fine,
and then one day,

328
00:15:47,404 --> 00:15:49,711
I realized that
I was totally alone.

329
00:15:49,976 --> 00:15:53,107
I'd lost everything.
I lost my-my wife,

330
00:15:53,194 --> 00:15:54,444
my brother.

331
00:15:55,687 --> 00:15:56,791
Thank you.

332
00:15:57,101 --> 00:15:58,929
No further questions,
Your Honor.

333
00:16:02,140 --> 00:16:03,796
Mr. Raposa,

334
00:16:04,328 --> 00:16:07,624
do you know a man by the name
of Morton Clemmons?

335
00:16:07,936 --> 00:16:10,166
Mo Clemmons? Yeah.

336
00:16:10,254 --> 00:16:11,499
Yeah, sure. I know him.

337
00:16:11,587 --> 00:16:14,171
He is a loan officer,
isn't he?

338
00:16:14,389 --> 00:16:16,710
Have you ever approached
him about a loan?

339
00:16:16,798 --> 00:16:18,583
Objection. Relevance?

340
00:16:18,671 --> 00:16:19,889
Uh, Your Honor,

341
00:16:20,045 --> 00:16:23,092
the witness testified
that he suddenly decided

342
00:16:23,180 --> 00:16:24,790
to tell this story
about my client

343
00:16:24,878 --> 00:16:26,585
because of a change in the law.

344
00:16:26,706 --> 00:16:29,926
I intend to prove
that there is, in fact,

345
00:16:30,013 --> 00:16:31,905
another reason for his suit.

346
00:16:32,326 --> 00:16:35,278
I'll allow. The witness
will answer the question.

347
00:16:36,546 --> 00:16:38,108
Yes, I applied
for a loan at the bank,

348
00:16:38,195 --> 00:16:39,739
and he was
the loan officer,

349
00:16:39,827 --> 00:16:41,246
- yes.
- In fact,

350
00:16:41,343 --> 00:16:45,146
you borrowed $15,000,
didn't you?

351
00:16:45,448 --> 00:16:48,607
Yes. I retired
from the service a year ago.

352
00:16:48,695 --> 00:16:50,831
I wanted a change of pace.

353
00:16:50,919 --> 00:16:52,217
I wanted to see
my brother more often,

354
00:16:52,304 --> 00:16:54,741
so I bought a body shop
with my savings,

355
00:16:54,829 --> 00:16:56,560
but the equipment,

356
00:16:57,737 --> 00:16:59,200
it needed some upgrades, so...

357
00:16:59,338 --> 00:17:02,630
So you borrowed $15,000

358
00:17:02,742 --> 00:17:05,646
and you have not been able
to make those payments

359
00:17:05,734 --> 00:17:07,823
in a timely fashion,
have you?

360
00:17:08,192 --> 00:17:10,255
Well, I think I have, mostly.

361
00:17:13,132 --> 00:17:15,090
The last 90 days,
it's been tricky.

362
00:17:15,482 --> 00:17:18,011
My-my brother didn't have
insurance, so I had to pay

363
00:17:18,099 --> 00:17:20,560
for his last round of rehab,
plus the funeral.

364
00:17:20,648 --> 00:17:22,482
I have alimony payments.

365
00:17:22,570 --> 00:17:25,138
The bank threatened to repossess
your shop, didn't they?

366
00:17:28,004 --> 00:17:30,794
Do you recognize
these e-mails

367
00:17:30,882 --> 00:17:33,624
between you
and Mr. Clemmons?

368
00:17:34,771 --> 00:17:36,153
Sure. Yeah.

369
00:17:36,241 --> 00:17:38,755
And would you read
the last one for me,

370
00:17:38,911 --> 00:17:42,262
the one sent on
the very morning you filed

371
00:17:42,358 --> 00:17:43,810
this lawsuit?

372
00:17:44,050 --> 00:17:46,450
"Seriously,
no need for the repo talk.

373
00:17:46,538 --> 00:17:49,099
"I have a plan. I'll have the
funds by the end of the month,

374
00:17:49,187 --> 00:17:50,232
guaranteed."

375
00:17:50,626 --> 00:17:53,114
"By the end of the month,
guaranteed."

376
00:17:54,383 --> 00:17:58,232
Where was this cash
going to come from, Mr. Raposa?

377
00:17:58,535 --> 00:18:00,015
My client?

378
00:18:00,297 --> 00:18:03,430
Was your plan
to slander Mr. Maybrook

379
00:18:03,541 --> 00:18:05,503
so that you could
get your hands

380
00:18:05,591 --> 00:18:07,110
on the money you needed?

381
00:18:07,197 --> 00:18:09,466
No, of course not.

382
00:18:09,554 --> 00:18:13,123
I was going to sell
some machinery, maybe,

383
00:18:13,334 --> 00:18:15,728
or maybe try
to borrow

384
00:18:15,815 --> 00:18:18,138
a loan against
my army pension.

385
00:18:18,226 --> 00:18:20,630
Try? Maybe?

386
00:18:21,335 --> 00:18:24,338
Sounds very different
from the "guarantee"

387
00:18:24,519 --> 00:18:26,021
you promise in that e-mail.

388
00:18:26,130 --> 00:18:29,829
I was buying time,
so I exaggerated a little.

389
00:18:29,932 --> 00:18:31,372
Oh, you exaggerated a little?

390
00:18:32,740 --> 00:18:34,302
You exaggerated.

391
00:18:34,751 --> 00:18:37,449
Turns out he exaggerated,
ladies and gentlemen,

392
00:18:37,537 --> 00:18:41,367
misrepresented the truth so that
he could get what he wanted.

393
00:18:41,525 --> 00:18:45,387
I wonder what else he has
misrepresented here today.

394
00:18:45,475 --> 00:18:46,911
- Objection.
- Sustained.

395
00:18:46,999 --> 00:18:49,130
Jury will disregard.

396
00:18:49,413 --> 00:18:50,588
Did they?

397
00:18:50,675 --> 00:18:53,216
Nope. Not a one of them.

398
00:18:53,608 --> 00:18:55,741
Every green is gone, Bull.

399
00:19:01,747 --> 00:19:04,956
Suggesting that a man is lying
about his being abused

400
00:19:05,044 --> 00:19:07,114
because he has
money problems...

401
00:19:07,903 --> 00:19:10,184
How does an attorney put that
out there with a straight face?

402
00:19:10,271 --> 00:19:12,153
Because, sadly,
it works.

403
00:19:12,403 --> 00:19:13,840
Fills the jury
with doubt,

404
00:19:13,927 --> 00:19:16,146
and the truth is, we might be
employing the same strategy

405
00:19:16,233 --> 00:19:17,408
if we were
representing Maybrook.

406
00:19:17,495 --> 00:19:20,137
Except I would never be
Maybrook's attorney.

407
00:19:20,317 --> 00:19:21,884
Defend someone
who hurts children?

408
00:19:21,972 --> 00:19:23,794
That would
never happen.

409
00:19:25,341 --> 00:19:26,809
But it did work,
didn't it?

410
00:19:27,157 --> 00:19:28,606
Mm.

411
00:19:29,115 --> 00:19:31,214
Hopefully,
Danny's potential witness

412
00:19:31,302 --> 00:19:32,771
will be waiting for us
back at the office,

413
00:19:32,858 --> 00:19:36,426
and with any luck, his story
will sound enough like Stephen's

414
00:19:36,514 --> 00:19:38,212
to resonate with the jury.

415
00:19:38,512 --> 00:19:40,995
It was a couple of nights
after the Captain's Dinner.

416
00:19:41,083 --> 00:19:43,958
His assistant Lydia
said he wanted to see me.

417
00:19:45,052 --> 00:19:46,873
I can't lie.

418
00:19:47,161 --> 00:19:48,657
I was pretty excited.

419
00:19:49,255 --> 00:19:50,364
Why's that?

420
00:19:50,528 --> 00:19:53,488
'Cause my family was poor
and Maybrook wasn't.

421
00:19:53,825 --> 00:19:56,883
He had a Sega,
he had a PS1,

422
00:19:57,239 --> 00:20:00,538
all these cool cameras,
his very own darkroom.

423
00:20:00,848 --> 00:20:03,541
And I had heard sometimes
he let kids drink his liquor.

