00:20:33,856 --> 00:20:36,574
Sure. All the time.

436
00:20:36,817 --> 00:20:39,186
At first, it was small stuff.

437
00:20:39,434 --> 00:20:43,309
He'd rub my shoulders,
squeeze my arm.

438
00:20:43,794 --> 00:20:44,917
I see.

439
00:20:45,005 --> 00:20:49,457
And did it get more intimate,
more sexual?

440
00:20:52,982 --> 00:20:54,552
Yeah.

441
00:20:54,919 --> 00:20:56,286
Of course.

442
00:20:58,849 --> 00:21:00,971
Can you describe
these interactions

443
00:21:01,059 --> 00:21:02,575
you had with Maybrook?

444
00:21:03,067 --> 00:21:04,880
There was no interaction.

445
00:21:05,777 --> 00:21:08,041
That would imply
two people participating.

446
00:21:08,128 --> 00:21:11,458
There was just him
getting you drunk,

447
00:21:11,719 --> 00:21:14,983
getting you high,
and taking what he wanted.

448
00:21:15,474 --> 00:21:17,180
I know it must be difficult,

449
00:21:17,496 --> 00:21:19,403
but if you could just
tell us about that.

450
00:21:20,770 --> 00:21:23,184
What he did,
how he did it.

451
00:21:24,224 --> 00:21:25,513
How it felt?

452
00:21:29,062 --> 00:21:32,003
I'm sorry. I know
this is really difficult,

453
00:21:32,091 --> 00:21:33,537
and I don't mean
to make you uncomfortable,

454
00:21:33,624 --> 00:21:37,554
but it's incredibly important
that the jury... hear from someone,

455
00:21:37,642 --> 00:21:40,447
anyone, other than our client.

456
00:21:41,072 --> 00:21:43,815
Someone who's been
victimized by Maybrook.

457
00:21:44,127 --> 00:21:45,556
You understand that?

458
00:21:46,601 --> 00:21:47,645
If we don't ask you,

459
00:21:47,740 --> 00:21:50,047
the other side will.

460
00:21:58,796 --> 00:22:00,920
My wife was right.
I'm sorry, I can't.

461
00:22:01,007 --> 00:22:02,171
I-I just can't do this.

462
00:22:02,259 --> 00:22:03,659
Did you think
you wouldn't be asked?

463
00:22:03,762 --> 00:22:05,492
I guess I was hoping

464
00:22:05,580 --> 00:22:07,147
it would be good enough
if I showed up.

465
00:22:07,749 --> 00:22:09,757
I don't actually think I
could go up in front

466
00:22:09,845 --> 00:22:11,657
of a courtroom full of people
and go into details.

467
00:22:11,744 --> 00:22:12,654
But Alan,

468
00:22:12,742 --> 00:22:15,411
without your testimony,
it is our client's word

469
00:22:15,499 --> 00:22:17,117
against Maybrook's.

470
00:22:17,414 --> 00:22:19,343
He doesn't stand
a chance.

471
00:22:20,461 --> 00:22:21,874
I know.

472
00:22:25,017 --> 00:22:27,015
But if I answer that question,

473
00:22:27,816 --> 00:22:31,156
if I say those things
out loud, in court,

474
00:22:32,226 --> 00:22:34,328
in a room full of strangers,

475
00:22:35,868 --> 00:22:38,088
how long before
the whole world looks at me

476
00:22:38,445 --> 00:22:40,335
and only sees what happened?

477
00:22:41,671 --> 00:22:43,140
Sees a victim?

478
00:22:44,226 --> 00:22:46,328
Not the success
that I've become...

479
00:22:50,289 --> 00:22:52,749
...but the broken kid
I used to be.

480
00:22:56,149 --> 00:22:57,843
The gullible child

481
00:22:58,151 --> 00:23:01,968
Maybrook did horrible things to.

482
00:23:04,968 --> 00:23:06,367
Look,

483
00:23:06,548 --> 00:23:09,445
if it were just me,
maybe.

484
00:23:10,467 --> 00:23:13,656
But I have a wife
to think about. Kids.

485
00:23:14,468 --> 00:23:17,406
How could I explain
all this to my kids?

486
00:23:18,999 --> 00:23:21,169
I'm sorry. I-I wish
you and your client

487
00:23:21,257 --> 00:23:22,390
all the luck in the world.

488
00:23:22,478 --> 00:23:25,133
And I'm sorry
I wasted your time.

489
00:23:27,929 --> 00:23:30,062
U-Uh, let me walk you out.

490
00:23:36,203 --> 00:23:37,799
Please sit.

491
00:23:38,421 --> 00:23:40,932
Mr. Colón, you may
call your next witness.

492
00:23:41,343 --> 00:23:44,110
Uh, Your Honor, the
witness we had scheduled

493
00:23:44,197 --> 00:23:46,880
is no longer available
to testify at this time.

494
00:23:46,968 --> 00:23:48,849
We request
a continuance

495
00:23:48,937 --> 00:23:51,421
in order to secure
an adequate replacement.

496
00:23:51,835 --> 00:23:54,974
Due to the backlog on this
court's docket, and the fact

497
00:23:55,062 --> 00:23:58,117
that the events at issue here
occurred 24 years ago,

498
00:23:58,249 --> 00:24:00,732
I feel this case cannot
afford further delay.

499
00:24:00,820 --> 00:24:01,779
I'm denying
your request.

500
00:24:01,866 --> 00:24:04,437
Uh, respectfully,

501
00:24:04,664 --> 00:24:07,742
Your Honor, though the
events of this case happened

502
00:24:07,829 --> 00:24:12,007
a long time ago, the lookback
window opened just recently.

503
00:24:12,390 --> 00:24:14,646
We've been working under
a condensed time line,

504
00:24:14,734 --> 00:24:16,568
and we had no way
of predicting

505
00:24:16,656 --> 00:24:18,622
this turn of events
with our witness.

506
00:24:18,749 --> 00:24:21,495
Well... Be that as it may,
do you have any other witnesses

507
00:24:21,582 --> 00:24:23,714
at your disposal
at this time?

508
00:24:24,882 --> 00:24:26,045
No, Your Honor.

509
00:24:26,195 --> 00:24:27,234
Ms. Grossman,

510
00:24:27,334 --> 00:24:29,285
is the defense prepared
to call its first witness?

511
00:24:29,372 --> 00:24:30,968
We are, Your Honor.

512
00:24:31,244 --> 00:24:33,460
The defense calls
Peter Maybrook.

513
00:24:34,212 --> 00:24:37,607
The inclination
for opening the camp?

514
00:24:37,695 --> 00:24:39,966
I think that's pretty clear.

515
00:24:40,054 --> 00:24:42,708
I don't want to bore
the jury with my story.

516
00:24:42,796 --> 00:24:44,843
I'm pretty sure that
you've heard it before.

517
00:24:44,931 --> 00:24:50,130
But the essence of it is,
I grew up in the projects.

518
00:24:50,218 --> 00:24:51,404
No dad.

519
00:24:51,492 --> 00:24:53,583
Mom who wouldn't
come home

520
00:24:53,671 --> 00:24:54,963
for days at a time.

521
00:24:55,050 --> 00:24:56,646
But when you're growing up,

522
00:24:56,734 --> 00:25:00,273
you don't know that
any of that's not normal.

523
00:25:00,523 --> 00:25:01,622
I'm sure I don't need

524
00:25:01,709 --> 00:25:03,406
to tell you,
but they love this guy.

525
00:25:03,493 --> 00:25:05,919
Anyway, when I was 13,

526
00:25:06,007 --> 00:25:07,410
I was picked to go

527
00:25:07,497 --> 00:25:09,238
to a fresh air camp upstate

528
00:25:09,325 --> 00:25:11,742
for two weeks in the summer.

529
00:25:13,835 --> 00:25:15,367
Changed everything.

530
00:25:16,655 --> 00:25:17,890
Saved my life.

531
00:25:18,893 --> 00:25:21,701
There was a counselor
up there who...

532
00:25:21,789 --> 00:25:24,242
don't ask me why...
He took an interest in me.

533
00:25:24,345 --> 00:25:25,977
I know it's been almost
a quarter-century,

534
00:25:26,064 --> 00:25:28,529
but I swear this is word
for word the same nonsense

535
00:25:28,617 --> 00:25:30,738
he spewed on the
first day of camp.

536
00:25:30,825 --> 00:25:32,704
...and put me
on a horse

537
00:25:32,792 --> 00:25:33,963
for the first time.

538
00:25:35,202 --> 00:25:40,296
And then, after the two weeks
was up, he stayed in touch.

539
00:25:40,414 --> 00:25:41,618
Wrote me letters,

540
00:25:41,705 --> 00:25:44,219
called me on the phone,
asked me

541
00:25:44,307 --> 00:25:45,471
about school.

542
00:25:45,559 --> 00:25:48,158
Even dropped by
once in a while.

543
00:25:48,364 --> 00:25:50,666
Things that nobody else
was doing.

544
00:25:50,820 --> 00:25:53,431
<i>The combination of that man,</i>

545
00:25:53,519 --> 00:25:56,127
and that experience gave me

546
00:25:56,215 --> 00:26:01,768
the ability to see a future,
which was something

547
00:26:01,856 --> 00:26:04,174
I-I had never really
contemplated before.

548
00:26:04,331 --> 00:26:08,248
So when I started
experiencing all my success,

549
00:26:08,336 --> 00:26:09,619
I just thought,

550
00:26:10,149 --> 00:26:13,596
I want to recreate that
experience for someone else.

551
00:26:14,182 --> 00:26:16,549
I want to give back.

552
00:26:16,698 --> 00:26:17,750
Objection!

553
00:26:17,838 --> 00:26:19,178
Relevance, Your Honor.

554
00:26:19,265 --> 00:26:22,268
This is a sexual assault
and battery trial,

555
00:26:22,355 --> 00:26:23,930
not a testimonial dinner.

556
00:26:24,018 --> 00:26:25,391
What-what are we
listening to here?

557
00:26:25,479 --> 00:26:26,359
Your Honor,

558
00:26:26,446 --> 00:26:28,317
the plaintiff and his attorney
are painting

559
00:26:28,404 --> 00:26:31,752
Mr. Maybrook's camp like
some kind of den of iniquity.

560
00:26:31,840 --> 00:26:33,901
- It's only fair that I be...
- Enough.

561
00:26:33,989 --> 00:26:36,953
Both of you. On this point,
I'm finding myself agreeing

562
00:26:37,041 --> 00:26:38,022
with Mr. Colón.

563
00:26:38,109 --> 00:26:40,330
Let's move it along,
Ms. Grossman.

564
00:26:40,418 --> 00:26:44,463
Fine. Mr. Maybrook,
did you host private dinners

565
00:26:44,551 --> 00:26:47,002
for the cabin captains
at your estate?

566
00:26:47,090 --> 00:26:48,869
I did. Yes.

567
00:26:48,957 --> 00:26:51,992
These young men had
achieved something.

568
00:26:52,080 --> 00:26:54,300
I felt it was important
to show them

569
00:26:54,510 --> 00:26:56,650
that hard work reaped rewards.

570
00:26:56,737 --> 00:27:00,044
The plaintiff has asserted
that you invited him back

571
00:27:00,131 --> 00:27:02,395
to your house alone
on several occasions.

572
00:27:02,635 --> 00:27:04,005
Is that also true?

573
00:27:04,213 --> 00:27:08,314
It is. You have to remember,
this was almost 25 years ago.

574
00:27:08,432 --> 00:27:10,968
The social mores have changed,

575
00:27:11,096 --> 00:27:15,688
but at the time, it wasn't
unusual for a responsible adult

576
00:27:15,776 --> 00:27:18,533
to be alone with a young person
in his charge.

577
00:27:18,621 --> 00:27:21,104
That all sounds
very reasonable to me.

578
00:27:21,234 --> 00:27:25,151
But I would be remiss
if I did not ask this question:

579
00:27:25,239 --> 00:27:30,625
Mr. Maybrook, do you have
any idea why Mr. Raposa

580
00:27:30,713 --> 00:27:34,905
was able to describe
your bathroom in such detail?

581
00:27:35,080 --> 00:27:37,560
What he said about the camper's
wash cabins was true.

582
00:27:37,647 --> 00:27:39,619
Their hot water
was inconsistent.

583
00:27:39,877 --> 00:27:42,688
So some of the young men
would occasionally ask

584
00:27:42,776 --> 00:27:45,494
to use my shower,
and I let them.

585
00:27:45,829 --> 00:27:49,005
Maybe-maybe I shouldn't have.

586
00:27:49,646 --> 00:27:51,582
And when you
allowed one of these campers

587
00:27:51,669 --> 00:27:54,130
to shower in
your residence...

588
00:27:55,535 --> 00:27:59,685
...did you ever have
occasion to join them?

589
00:27:59,840 --> 00:28:02,388
- Oh...
- To shower with them?

590
00:28:02,476 --> 00:28:03,825
My God, of course not.

591
00:28:03,913 --> 00:28:07,265
Then how do you account
for Mr. Raposa's testimony?

592
00:28:07,384 --> 00:28:09,692
I-I can't,
because it simply isn't true.

593
00:28:09,780 --> 00:28:11,608
Now,
are-are you saying that

594
00:28:11,696 --> 00:28:13,959
you recollect it differently?

595
00:28:14,661 --> 00:28:18,685
Look, I remember Mr. Raposa.

596
00:28:19,896 --> 00:28:23,563
He was a promising
young man.

597
00:28:23,802 --> 00:28:27,567
I simply wanted
to help him, period.

598
00:28:27,841 --> 00:28:32,485
So it's heartbreaking to hear
him lying about me in this way.

599
00:28:32,572 --> 00:28:35,531
I can only guess
that he needs someone to blame

600
00:28:35,618 --> 00:28:38,136
for the way that his life
turned out.

601
00:28:38,224 --> 00:28:39,622
Objection. Witness

602
00:28:39,709 --> 00:28:40,754
is speculating.

603
00:28:40,841 --> 00:28:42,059
Sustained.

604
00:28:42,146 --> 00:28:44,540
The jury will disregard
Mr. Maybrook's comments.

605
00:28:45,599 --> 00:28:48,386
You say
Mr. Raposa is lying.

606
00:28:48,474 --> 00:28:51,765
Why should the jury believe you
and not Mr. Raposa?

607
00:28:51,896 --> 00:28:54,942
Well, let's start with the fact
that I wasn't even there.

608
00:28:55,450 --> 00:28:57,894
I'm sorry,
how do you mean?

609
00:28:57,982 --> 00:29:00,295
The night that Mr. Raposa
keeps referencing,

610
00:29:00,382 --> 00:29:03,429
the night that Michael Johnson
won the gold in the 400

611
00:29:03,516 --> 00:29:05,300
in the Atlanta Olympics?

612
00:29:05,387 --> 00:29:07,433
I remember it perfectly.

613
00:29:07,599 --> 00:29:12,786
Except it was early morning
where I was, in a pub in Dublin,

614
00:29:12,927 --> 00:29:16,442
celebrating a new store opening
with my international team.

615
00:29:16,529 --> 00:29:19,619
Order, please.

616
00:29:19,706 --> 00:29:22,143
Your
Honor, I would like

617
00:29:22,230 --> 00:29:26,495
to enter this stamped
passport into evidence,

618
00:29:26,582 --> 00:29:31,805
which documents the fact
that Mr. Maybrook was,

619
00:29:32,099 --> 00:29:37,487
in fact, out of the country
from mid-July

620
00:29:37,575 --> 00:29:39,886
through early
August 1996,

621
00:29:39,974 --> 00:29:44,325
the exact time Mr. Raposa's
alleged abuse took place.

622
00:29:44,644 --> 00:29:45,925
So entered.

623
00:29:52,154 --> 00:29:54,792
It just doesn't make sense. Do
we believe his passport's real?

624
00:29:54,910 --> 00:29:56,840
- He's a rich guy. Maybe...
- It's real.

625
00:29:56,928 --> 00:29:58,575
Our team authenticated it.

626
00:29:58,692 --> 00:30:01,237
Also found credit card receipts
and hotel records.

627
00:30:01,325 --> 00:30:02,927
Maybrook really was in Dublin.

628
00:30:03,576 --> 00:30:05,247
I don't understand.

629
00:30:05,566 --> 00:30:07,829
You know me, Marissa.
I-I didn't make this up.

630
00:30:07,917 --> 00:30:08,911
I'm not a liar.

631
00:30:08,999 --> 00:30:10,958
Of course you didn't.
Of course you aren't.

632
00:30:11,549 --> 00:30:13,638
Look, I spent years
telling people

633
00:30:13,804 --> 00:30:16,114
I met my adoptive mom
on my ninth birthday.

634
00:30:16,202 --> 00:30:17,464
Years.

635
00:30:17,778 --> 00:30:19,935
I remembered that day
so clearly.

636
00:30:20,209 --> 00:30:22,253
My foster mom threw a plate
at my head that morning

637
00:30:22,341 --> 00:30:23,441
because the dishes weren't done.

638
00:30:23,528 --> 00:30:25,301
Got me right here.

639
00:30:25,388 --> 00:30:28,247
Anyway, that afternoon
at school, there was cake.

640
00:30:28,739 --> 00:30:32,107
I wished on those candles with
all my might for a new family.

641
00:30:32,880 --> 00:30:34,948
And who was at the social
worker's office that night

642
00:30:35,036 --> 00:30:36,456
but my new mom.

643
00:30:36,593 --> 00:30:38,291
Wow. That's amazing.

644
00:30:38,402 --> 00:30:40,058
It's also not true.

645
00:30:40,792 --> 00:30:43,259
A few years back, I was
going through old paperwork,

646
00:30:43,347 --> 00:30:45,016
and realized I hadn't
actually met my mom

647
00:30:45,103 --> 00:30:46,730
until I was nearly ten.

648
00:30:47,464 --> 00:30:50,020
Memory. It's malleable.

649
00:30:50,542 --> 00:30:52,545
Especially when it comes
to children.

650
00:30:52,730 --> 00:30:55,157
Especially when it comes
to trauma.

651
00:30:56,106 --> 00:30:57,636
So what does this mean
for my case?

652
00:30:57,724 --> 00:30:59,456
It means we call
a rebuttal witness.

653
00:30:59,596 --> 00:31:01,558
It's why we asked
for a day's continuance,

654
00:31:01,772 --> 00:31:04,665
so we can line up some experts
who can explain to the jury

655
00:31:04,753 --> 00:31:07,938
that PTSD can lead to the
repression of some memories

656
00:31:08,026 --> 00:31:10,172
and the conflation of others.

657
00:31:10,722 --> 00:31:12,175
Don't worry.

658
00:31:13,131 --> 00:31:14,573
We'll get through this.

659
00:31:15,133 --> 00:31:16,589
We're not done.

660
00:31:19,174 --> 00:31:22,009
Oh.

661
00:31:22,097 --> 00:31:23,359
Hallelujah.

662
00:31:23,667 --> 00:31:24,838
You have to share.

663
00:31:24,940 --> 00:31:26,394
The child psychologist

664
00:31:26,482 --> 00:31:28,292
I reached out to,
the one who specializes

665
00:31:28,380 --> 00:31:29,587
in trauma and memory?

666
00:31:29,675 --> 00:31:31,565
She just texted "yes."

667
00:31:32,104 --> 00:31:34,321
She's agreed
to meet with Stephen,

668
00:31:34,409 --> 00:31:36,111
and if that meeting goes well,

669
00:31:36,198 --> 00:31:37,895
she's willing to testify
on his behalf.

670
00:31:38,378 --> 00:31:40,637
If only that were
all there was to it.

671
00:31:40,925 --> 00:31:42,378
What are you talking about?

672
00:31:43,167 --> 00:31:45,033
Maybrook's attorney
just e-mailed me

673
00:31:45,120 --> 00:31:46,730
an updated witness list.

674
00:31:46,893 --> 00:31:48,549
There are more names
on here

675
00:31:48,667 --> 00:31:50,355
than the credits
of a Marvel movie.

676
00:31:52,363 --> 00:31:54,452
Camp alumni, former staffers,

677
00:31:54,540 --> 00:31:56,107
his head of
philanthropic giving.

678
00:31:56,195 --> 00:31:58,362
All people who are gonna
sing Maybrook's praises

679
00:31:58,450 --> 00:32:00,017
to the high heavens.

680
00:32:00,215 --> 00:32:02,478
Got it.
She's gonna inundate the jury

681
00:32:02,566 --> 00:32:03,651
with character witnesses.

682
00:32:03,739 --> 00:32:06,105
So by the time
we get our shot at rebuttal,

683
00:32:06,193 --> 00:32:08,055
the jury will be so weary,
they won't even hear

684
00:32:08,143 --> 00:32:09,315
what we have to say.

685
00:32:09,403 --> 00:32:10,690
Wait a second.

686
00:32:11,066 --> 00:32:13,269
Is this the entire list?
Is this everyone?

687
00:32:13,652 --> 00:32:15,519
It's three pages long, Taylor.
You want more?

688
00:32:15,607 --> 00:32:16,696
No, I just...

689
00:32:16,799 --> 00:32:19,064
Lydia Helms,
his former assistant.

690
00:32:19,152 --> 00:32:20,839
How come she's not on the list?

691
00:32:21,385 --> 00:32:22,753
Lydia.

692
00:32:23,378 --> 00:32:25,027
She's the one
Stephen talked about.

693
00:32:25,115 --> 00:32:27,542
Mr. Coleman, the other night
in my office.

694
00:32:28,095 --> 00:32:29,737
She would make the approach.

